(27981, ' [quote=Bluff]well i think baikal semi and over/under are  a bit heavy for trap and skeet.... i ll prefer any light weight gun over under , which is easier to swing and followup.[/quote]\n\nBluff Bhai, u got u''r theory all wrong, trap/skeet/sporting clay guns are intentionally built heavier. a heavier gun swings smooth, promotes a smooth followup and since recoil is inversly propotional to the gun''s weight, a heavier gun reduces recoil significantly.\n\nnow u finally understand why some trap/skeet players add lead weights to their shotguns. their objective is it to make it heavier, they do so by installing lead weghts used by wheel balancers. in almost all international matches, guns can weigh upto whoping 9-10 pounds. now thats heavy my friend. lead weights can do wonders for ur gun if u''r gun is light.\n\nhunting guns however are build light cause they need to be carried all over long/vast distances. plus in real hunting scenarios high volume shooting is a distant probability, so \nhigher kick/recol associated with a lighter gun isnt that important variable to consider.\n\n\n[quote]I think comparing DARRA guns with Turkish is also the work of patriotism. They both do reverse engenering but DARRA people neither have access to modern machines nor to the proper metal. On the other hand Turkish plants are manufecturing some weapons at NATO standard for their troops. Turkish companies have knowledge sharing with the worlds best companies like Stoeger is a subsidery of BERETTA. Turkish walnut is considered one of the best.[/quote]\n\nsir, thats what i said, turkish gunmaking facilities are basically our darra type facilities, however they are more techologically advanced, they got CNC machines in 2001 (courtesy of USA not italy). they are getting better at metallurgy (again courtesy of USA) and thats it. Turkey is not a signatory to CIP, their guns are not proof tested, there is no one to guarantee the safety of their firearms. there are no formal testing standards. (now u know why turkish guns dont carry proof marks/stamps). now dont tell me "proof tested at 12000 psi" stamped on turkish barrels counts for something cause no it does not.\n\none more thing, stoeger plant was not established by beretta, it was in actuality, bought as a fully functional entity by beretta. that ends the debate that beretta quality guns are being produced their. beretta bought a cheaper company to expand their reach to lower price shotgun market. thats it folks, thats it.\n\n[quote]As far as the use of guns in competitions is considered it is not the quality of russian guns that take them to the events, but the patriotic competitors of the Russian block who were not allowed to use anyother gun.[/quote]\n\nsorry sir, european (specially britain, spain, french, even italian) players have intentionally opted for russian guns in international tournaments, not just russian block players. TSKIB buys shotguns made by IMZ and customizes them, some of those shotguns have been listed at over $20-$50K per piece. infact, some of the most important innovations were done at IMZ, remember the jug choke? that jug choke was developed at TSKIB, made russia win olympic skeet 4 times in a row. and the gun was baikal IZH27.\n\nAK47, draganov SVD, tigr, saiga type guns are just a small part of what IZMASH does. talk space technology, mobile launching pads, tanks, cars, motor bikes, medical equipment, pace makers. and the list is quiet long my friend.\n\nRegards.', ''),
