(28302, ' Any kind of game tastes good it is marinated overnight in a mixture of yoghurt, ground black pepper, salt, ground turmeric, ginger and garlic paste, and slow roasted in an oven the following day. The meat should be placed in a suitably big stainless steel pan and basted with some olive oil or desi ghee, and accompanied by whole onions, potatoes, tomatoes and some green chillies, and the whole thing sealed airtight with three wraps of aluminum foil. \n\nPlace this dish on the second grill of your oven, while on the bottom of the oven you may keep a smaller pan full of water. This helps prevent hot spots in the oven and the meat from drying up if you accidently left the flame too high.\n\nTwo hours of roasting for every kg of meat is a good yardstick to go by for game meat, though some require more, and some require less. If you have wrapped the pan properly. you will notice that after a few hours the foil will start ballooning, and after a while it will look bloated, and soon steam will start escaping it. At this point in time, turn the flame down gradually till you can see only a wisp of steam escaping from your roasting pan. \n\nNow once 75% of the roasting time has elapsed, say three hours, if you are roasting a 2 kg gazelle leg, make a small slit in the centre of the foil with a knife, and try poking a wooden toothpick in the meat, if it simply in all the way through to the bone, with ease, your roast is done. Now remove the foil, and if there is too much gravy for your taste, dry it up removing that small pan of water, and turning up the flame. If it''s just right, turn off the oven, pull out the roast and serve it. \n\nSuch roasts are best enjoyed with hot naan, like minded people and the beverage of your choice!!\n\n \nLast but not the least, remember one thing - the lower the flame, slower you roast, the longer you roast, and the easier you go on the spices, the more delicious, the roast shall be.', ''),
