(29121, ' [quote]Nice ibex! I once picked up a 47" horns on a hillside in Sindh. The animal had died a natural death.[/quote]\n\nDear Turumti\nIf this is 47 it is either a world record or perhaps 2nd or 3rd one in the row but definitely among the top five trophies of the world. However, since its not a hunted trophy it won''t be and can''t listed. Yet since you found it in wilderness it''s not a crime as bad as poaching ... lol ! I don''t know the fresh record but the last standing world record of Sindh Ibex was 45 inches by Chris Boddington. Can you show me photos of these horns .. Turumti ?', ''),
(29122, ' These days it seems that every manufacturer out there is selling shotguns with all the proper goodies.  Good.  But if you want the best and i do mean the best - it has to be a NO NONSENSE weapon.  Here are three that have been "tried and true... to form and function".\n\n1.  Remington 870 police pump.\n2.  Remington 1100 and the 1187 series.\n3.  Benelli M1 Super 90 Tactical.\n\nThe spas (too heavy), Benelli M3 (nice confusing gadgets), and many others like it have features in it but DO fall short on some item or function.', ''),
(29124, ' Kaiser,  \n\nThese horns were duly given to the Wildlife Department. I dont know what has become of them since.  This was not the only occasion I have found horns. In another valley, I found at least six ibex horns, two months after a flood ripped through the area. Only one pair  (37"& 35") were intact, the other were single split from each other,, and in the 30"-40" range. You would be surprised to learn that we did not find these horns in the river bed, rather there were entangled in bushes about  eight feet above. Since there was no accompanying carcass, I can only assume that these horns were from animals long dead and had been washed down the hills in the floods. \n\nFinally, sir, please explain "Yet since you found it in wilderness it''s not a crime as bad as poaching". Thank you.', ''),
