(30853, ' excellent work 12 gauge. Just to add to the above mentioned information about the fit of the shotgun i would add few simple things. To my understanding the most important measurments of the shotgun with refference to its fit are LOP(Length of pull), DAC(Drop at comb) and cast. To check that which one is required to be adjusted following things can be done.\n\nFirstly, to check the length of the pull. Bend your shooting arm at right angle the way a bodybuilder shows his mussels. Hold your shotgun in such a way that butt of the gun rests on your arm and receiver of the gun touches your palm and barrel straight up. Now first joint of your index finger must touch the trigger of the gun, if it does length of pull is right for you. If it touches above your first joint of the fingger it needs to be reduced and it needs to be increased if it touches below the joint. Length of pull is the easiest to be changed as some guns come with spacers or you can use a longer or shorter recoil pad as wel. Length of the pull is greatly dependent on the hight of the shooter, length of his arms, his body weight  and the length of his hands. \n\nSecondly, to check the drop at comb(DAC) just close your eyes and mount your shotgun. Now open your eyes and look down the barrel of the shotgun. For an ideal DAC you must see the front beed fully neither too much of the rib nor too much of the back of the receiver. If you see too much of the back of the receiver of your gun, it means that DAC is low and it needs to be reduced (if the comb is adjustable just raise it ). I f you see too much of the rib it means that DAC is high and it needs to be increased(Just lower the comb to get an ideal sight of the front beed). If your gun does not come with an adjustable comb as almost all guns except some sporting models come with fixed combs you need an expert to do the job. You may ruin the beauty of your gun and at the same time can''t measure the exact change to be made.\n\nFinally, cast of the gun. It is the tilt of the butt towards the shooter or away from the shooter. Butts are tilted twards the shooters and a gun tilted towards the right hand shooter is said to be CAST OFF gun. As most of the guns are made for the right hand shooters so they can''t fit the lefties. For a left hand shooter cast will be required to be adjusted. This should also be done by an expert as amount of cast will depend on the built of th shooter.', ''),
