(30900, ' nice work Hassan Bhai, but allow me to correct a few things.\n\n[quote]Firstly, to check the length of the pull. Bend your shooting arm at right angle the way a bodybuilder shows his mussels. Hold your shotgun in such a way that butt of the gun rests on your arm and receiver of the gun touches your palm and barrel straight up. Now first joint of your index finger must touch the trigger of the gun[/quote]\n\na very common mistake among inexperienced gun fitters, first of all, this bending of arm test is only an informal test (sort of like checking the tyre pressure by pressing it down with a foot, if its firm, tire is probably ok, however it is no concrete evidence of adequate air pressure in the tyre). second, if one has to do this age old test, make sure to measure it up to the middle of the second segment of the index finger, it is never advised to measure it up to the first joint of the index finger. third, it is never advised to put the gun there to measure up, why? cause the weight of the gun will press the biceps down, allowing more length to be squeezed in.\n\nmoving on, brother, there are many variables to consider while selecting appropriate LOP, there is the distance between the joint (first joint, nearst to the palm) of the thumb and the nose of the operator when mounting the gun, a minimum of two inches and maximum of 5 inches.\n\nmoving on further more, another variable to consider, while mounting the end of the buttstock should slightly brush against u''r inncer bicep (unable to explain, actually it more like the inner side of u''r shoulder), only very slight brush, sorta like a slight tap, but it should not get snagged. or as an english gun fitter once told me, "sorta like fore play".\n\nmoving on a little further more on the LOP, when u mount the gun, u''r right elbow (assuming that u''r a right handed shooter) should be absolutely parallel to the middle of u''r body, or as the same gun fitter told me, u''r right nipple should be in the background of u''r right elbow lad\n\nnow i''m moving alot i guess on the LOP subject, well, then there are clothes to consider, thicker the clothes, LOP must be decreased accordingly, thinner the clothes, LOP is increased accordingly, now u know why the most experienced gun fitter insist that u bring u''r shooting clothes and take measurement with and without them (by without i mean, shirt off, naked torso)\n\n[quote]Butts are tilted twards the shooters and a gun tilted towards the right hand shooter is said to be CAST OFF gun[/quote]\n\nbutts are never tilted towards the shooter in any case, for a right handed shooter the butt is tilted towards right (cast off). for a left handed shooter, butts are tilted towards the left (cast on). see the above picture for cast off configuration( bottom and far right).\n\n[quote]For an ideal DAC you must see the front beed fully neither too much of the rib nor too much of the back of the receiver. If you see too much of the back of the receiver of your gun, it means that DAC is low and it needs to be reduced (if the comb is adjustable just raise it ). I f you see too much of the rib it means that DAC is high and it needs to be increased(Just lower the comb to get an ideal sight of the front beed).[/quote]\n\nhere u are dead smack on the target. however i must add that there are latest techniques to this, sometimes, operator cannot tell correctly what he is seeing. it is therefore advised to do pupil alignment test while aiming the gun. here the gun fitter asks u to mount the gun then sees the bead from the muzzle end of the barrel with pupil of the eye in the background, if everything is correct, bead should be right in the middle of the pupil (black/blue/green/brown portion of the eye).\n\ngun fitting is a proper science with a dab of art (my humble opinion). however this process no matter how lengthy and painful will do wonders for the operator.\n\nRegards.', ''),
