(30908, ' Hi 12gauge, glad you gave your valuable coments, i really appreciate it. I will try to explain things with my little knowledge about the shotguns. I will start from the point that is not disputeable.\n\nFirstly, your coments about the cast of the gun.\n[quote]\nbutts are never tilted towards the shooter in any case, for a right handed shooter the butt is tilted towards right (cast off). for a left handed shooter, butts are tilted towards the left (cast on). see the above picture for cast off configuration( bottom and far right).\n [/quote]\n\nFriend, this is what i said, you mistakenly took wrong. when we say cast towards the body of the shooter, CAST OFF will be tilted towards the body of the right hand shooter and CAST ON will be tilted towards the body of the left hand shooter. Look in both cases "TOWARDS THE BODY OF THE SHOOTER". You can do this test just by mounting a gun on your left shoulder and right shoulder and there is no need to do any rocket science.\n\nNow the length of pull thing. You have added so many things, so many uncalculated things. You said..\n[quote]Now first joint of your index finger must touch the trigger of the gun\na very common mistake among inexperienced gun fitters, first of all, this bending of arm test is only an informal test (sort of like checking the tyre pressure by pressing it down with a foot, if its firm, tire is probably ok, however it is no concrete evidence of adequate air pressure in the tyre). second, if one has to do this age old test, make sure to measure it up to the middle of the second segment of the index finger, it is never advised to measure it up to the first joint of the index finger. third, it is never advised to put the gun there to measure up, why? cause the weight of the gun will press the biceps down, allowing more length to be squeezed in.\n[/quote]\n\nStarting an argument with the example of cheking air pressure by a foot in a tyre to the measurement of length of pull by gun bedding test is just comparing apples with oranges. As there is no way that by just pressing tyre with foot you can come to an exact numerical reading but by doing a gun bedding test you come to an exact measure.\n\nIn my previous post i said...\n[quote]Length of the pull is greatly dependent on the hight of the shooter, length of his arms, his body weight  and the length of his hands.[/quote]\n\nYour all measurements are regarding these variables arent they?? Now if we want to discuss other specific detais that are for gun smiths i would love to participate. The simple things that i mentioned were within the scope of a shooter not a gunsmith.\n\nLet me explain things again and keep them simple at the same time. Most of the guns are manufectured with a length of pull of 14.5" to 14.75". This length of pull is ideal for a person with 5'' 9" hight 33" arms length and 165lbs weight or that person wears a 40 size suit. When a gun is mounted its receiver shouldn''t be less than 2-3" from shooters face. This is what we get from the shelf. Here, you know there is no need to measure the nose, cheek bone or collar bone of the shooter. When we try to check the fit of the gun we just try to chek if there is a sizeable difference and that can easily done by this simple test that i mentioned in my earlier post. As far as that squeeze of bicep of the shooter with the weight of the gun is considered i leave it to the fellow shooters to do this test and furnish us the measurements that they get. In my humble opinion that squeeze of musseles of bicep will be offset by the squeeze of the musseles of the shoulder when gun will be mounted. \n\nHope you will post the other formal test that you pointed on in your post.\n\nNow another thing, you mentioned in your post that you have customized your gun by adding 2" in its length of pull.\n[quote]p.s. i didnt even hire the services of a gun fitter, i did it myself, had to add two inches to the LOP of my guns, man! what  a difference it makes, makes shooting absolutely reflexive in nature.[/quote]\n\nThis seems very nice work, Will you please give us the total LOP of your gun and your hight, arms length and weight. You can skip length of your nose.... :). As even BAIKALS don''t come with a LOP less than 14", your addition of 2" to any normal gun will end up with a gun with at least 16" LOP making it suitable for a person with hight of 6'' 4" or with extra ordinary long arms.\n\nHope this discussion will help us.', ''),
