(30927, ' [quote]This seems very nice work, Will you please give us the total LOP of your gun and your hight, arms length and weight. You can skip length of your nose.... . As even BAIKALS don''t come with a LOP less than 14", your addition of 2" to any normal gun will end up with a gun with at least 16" LOP making it suitable for a person with hight of 6'' 4" or with extra ordinary long arms.[/quote]\n\nwhat a coincidence, i''m 6 feet 3 inches tall, I used to play basketball for the Punjab team, WAPDA team, Rawalpindi division basketball team, Pakistan International Public School abbottabad team. i''ve got extra ordinary long arms.\n\nmoving on, I absolutely agree with u on the figures u gave 14 1/2 to 14 3/4 LOP for a 5''8 to 5''10 average male. i also agree with u when u said that i''m solving the LOP problem from a gunsmith point of view. cant help it there, the ones i consulted were professional gunfitters. \n\nbut the things that i dont agree wid u:\n\n1. look at the above posted picture again, u''ll see that the butt is tilted away from the right handed shooter and similarly tilted away from the left handed shooter (cast off and cast on)\n\n2. sir u said that i''ve added so many uncalculated things, sorry to disappoint u sir but the variables/tests that i gave are actually considered by professional gunfitters, the one u gave, arm bedding, allow me to quote what gunsmiths think of arm bedding test.\n\n"That tells you the length between your arm and your trigger finger, not much about how the stock fits you when your gun is mounted"\n\nKENT SUTTON: master gunfitter at browning center, arnold missouri. fitting guns since last 39 years.\n\nI can post multiple quotes brother, gimme sometime, I''m searching for email responses that I got when i was learning the gun fitting philosphy. i''ll post those emails too. almost every gunfitter i contacted simply brushed aside this proceedure for measuring LOP by arm bedding. it is only considered as a crude approximation. I wish i could do some of the gun fit tests on u in person to show u how detailed and mathematical my tests are. dont worry, my tests dont hurt a bit. ;)\n\none more thing: there is a popular saying in a gunfitter''s world. "beware of the fitter that fits a gun without a pattern board"\n\n3. u mentioned squeeze of the bicep is offset by squeeze of the shoulder, consult a doctor brother, he''ll correct u, biecps squeeze far more than shoulder, here is how my doctor just explained to me:\n\nwhen u lift u''r arm up (parrel to the floor) u''r shoulders actually buldge out. try it, lift ur arm up and out u''r body and feel ur shoulder. in the same position feel u''r bicep, it''ll be all mushy while u''r shoulder muscle (the one u mentioned) will be hard. having said that, there is no such thing as offset.\n\n[quote]Hope you will post the other formal test that you pointed on in your post.[/quote]\n\nwhich formal test are we talking about brother, as i''ve said earlier, gun fitting is a science with a dab of art. informal tests are arm bedding, nipple alingment and the foreplay part that i''ve mentioned earlier. formal tests are:\n\n1. add 3.175mm to 361.95mm for every inch taller you are to a 5 feet 9 inch person. example say a person is 6 feet, he is three inches taller than a 5''9 person, he needs to:\n\n3*(3.175) + 361.95 = 371.475mm = 14.625 inch LOP (mathematical approximation only, now way guarentees perfect fit as it doesnt take into account sleeve length)\n\n2. eyeballing: funny story, gunfitters kept saying eyeballing and i actually thought that they want me to scare the shooter by eyeballing into submission, i thought maybe with eyeballing the shooter kinda agrees with you that the gun is fit. it was later that i discovered that they were talking about pupil alingment test. this pupil alignment tests are extremely accurate in determining gun fit. this is the first test done by almost all experienced gunfitters.\n\nRegards.', ''),
