(32327, ' Hello\nI read somewhere that these rounds have lethal stopping power and transform a 9mm gun into something very lethal. Comments / price/ availability would be highly appreciated.\nRegards', ''),
(32328, ' [quote=Imu10]i know adnan very well and adnan alo knows me very well but u know when it comes to business he never does anything he is expensive as his shop is in such a posh location like zamzama but still i can talk and ask for a favor from him \nand as for the rifle i dont know if u have a budget i would advic you to buy a [b]270 win [/b]bolt action this calibre will fullfill all ur plain hunting game needs available in pakistan 270 is a much better calibre than and much better hitting power and flatter trajectory than a 7mm but what is ur budget for a bolt action rifle ?[/quote]\n\n\nExcellent advice!! A 270 Win. is more than enough rifle for all Pakistani game, ranging from chinkara to Ibex and Urial.  Frankly hitting power (retained energy) at range between 100-200 yards matter a lot more than muzzle velocity and trajectory. There are many proponents of the relatively flat shooting 22-250, which is essentially a varmint calibre, but they will never tell you how many animals they have lost despite shooting them through and through (aar paar).  Therefore, it is better to be over-gunned  than under-gunned. \n\nIn terms of what available in the market these days, if you are looking for an all rounder rifle, with which you can take everything from chinkara, hogdeer, ibex, urial and wildboar,  your first choice shd be the 270, followed by 30-06, 308 and 7mm. \n\nHowever, in Pakistan, choice of rifle is often dictated by the choice of ammo available. Before you finalise your rifle, I would suggest you look for ammo - 130 grain soft nose for 270 Win, 150-168grain soft nose for 30-06, 140-145 grain soft nose for 7mm and 150-165 grain for 308. \n\nOnce you find a good batch of relatively fresh bullets in this weight range, buy abt 200 of them. Make them sure that they are from the same batch and the same weight and the same brand. Different bullets have different points of impact. For example, a 130 grain 270Win bullet made by Prvi Partizan might hit dead on at 200 yards through your rifle, but the same bullet made by Winchester may hit an inch higher. \n\nIdeally speaking, you should first buy your rifle and scope then shoot 5 shot groups of all different brands and weights available for you calibre to see which ones group the best at say 200 yards. For this exercise your rifle just needs to be bore sighted, and hitting the bull''s eye since you are interested in seeing which bullet your rifle prefers the most. Allow your rifle to cool down between the groups, as hot  barrels behave differently than cold ones, and may not give you a true group. \n\nOnce you have found the bullet your rifle likes the most, go out an buy hundreds of those, zero your scope on them, and then use those bullets for the rest of your rifle. \n\nHowever, this is in an ideal situation. In a country like Pakistan,. where you dont have much choice, you must first find a rifle you like, then look for suitable ammo. Once you have found the ammo, buy a large enough batch of it, say 200 bullets at least, then get your rifle and scope, zero your rifle.  And then hunt happily ever after.\n\nAvoid the temptation to collect a motley crew of bullets, as this will do you no good. It is much better to be skilled with one rifle and one bullet, than to be unskilled with several. Thoise who shoot one rifle and one bullet often have their freezers stocked, and their walls adorned with trophies. Those who collect guns and bullets, have just those.', ''),
