(33760, ' Kaiser Sahab, \n\nEven the best though of conservation plans in this country do not work at times because there are people who feel they must shoot everything that moves, especially carnivores and omnivorous animals like bears.  This is not hunting. It''s a actually a sickness of the mind, a psychological condition, a feeling of inadequacy, of not being man enough till you kill something bigger or braver than yourself, or then something with a bigger male organ or a higher libido. \n\nSince, prehistoric times there has been a misplaced notion that killing a lion or a tiger or any other big animal will bestow the hunter with that animals courage and sexual prowess. Which is why you see pictures of kings, princes and other public figures standing with rifle in hand, and a foot upon the deceased animal. \n\nKilling animals does not make a man, there are other more enduring tests of character.', ''),
(33761, ' I have heard of a 36" urial being taken by a local hunter. I didnt see the trophy, but I have little reason to doubt him, as the man has some of the best trophies you will ever see.\n\nAs for ibex, I think the largest so far has been a 52" shot a by a local hunter. \n\nFinally, regarding poaching, I consider shooting females and young ones poaching, shooting animals from helicopters is poaching. But a nice big male taken fairly is not poaching. It''s all a question of ethics.', ''),
