(34207, ' [quote=Offroader2323]nice to hear that you are succeeding in your job now i am relaxed that some guys like you are there to handle those influential people. One question remaining what if some local hunters or any hunter from all over Pakistan wants to hunt in those areas with permit (what is the procedure and incentives for local pak hunters).[/quote]\n\nDiamonds & Emralds are loved by billions of people around the world but the problem is they are so expensive, ... not everyone can buy them ! Similarly, ligitimate big game hunting is an expensive hobby & it is not for every body ! \n\nHowever, the only solution is to protect & conserve the animals through communitya based programs and let their population grow to such an extent that the communities will voluntarily sell the extra animals to Pakistanis at low cost. \n\nThis sounds like a dream but it has actually happened many of the Northern Conservancies & District of Jamshoro Sindh where speedy growth of Himalayan & Sindh Ibex has enabled the communities to sell them at a subsidized costs to Pakistanis ! \n\nFor example : For Sindhi Domicile holders, the Sindh Ibex is Rs 50,000/= For Non Sindhis it is Rs 100,000/= For Foreigners it is Rs 350,000/= .. so the difference visible. \n\nYou''''ll be surprised to know that in just a few of the highly populated conservancies of Colorado, every indigenous hunter can shoot ONE WHITE TAIL EVERYDAY ... this makes 365 Bucks a year ... in other places the quota is less (as per their population) ... and you know what''s the price of hunting permit ???  Surprisingly, it varies from US$ 5 per hunt to US$ 25 per year (for all hunts) ... whereas the residents of other states this fee is more and for foreigners it is even more .. it goes over several thousand dollars ... and so on ! \n\nTo enable such a luxury .. a small group of people  have to work hard to make a conservancy & then within a short period of 3 to 5 years the results are great !\n\nThe problem with Pakstanis is that most of us want to become Robin Hoods without getting any training or learning the thics of hunting and we would want to shoot anything which moves in wilderness ... regardless of what it is and we all want to shoot it free of cost & in big numbers so the result is obvious ... we lack Shikar every where in pakistan except for the protected areas !', ''),
