(34691, ' Barrel twist rate is critical in rifles, in handguns most have a twist of 1:12 , meaning one complete turn in 12 inches of travel, for a lay man the bullet will take one complete turn on it''s axis after travelling 12 inches in the barrel.\n\nIn rifles it could be as high as 1:7 like in M4/M14 rifles. This high twist rate produces a very fast spin on the bullet when it leaves the barrel to stabilize it during it''s flight in the air. Lighter bullets require higher spin for stability. A 5.56 Nato fired from a M4/M14 usually spins at around 180,000 rpm. A barrel with a very high twist rate, like 1:7 has a shorter barrel life and requires early replacement.\n\nMost rifles have a twist rate of 1:9, an AK has a twist rate of 1:9, so does G3.\n \nBarrel twist rate is a whole science. There are scientific formulas to compute barrel twist rate. It depends mostly on the Length of the bullet, diameter of the bullet, muzzle velocity, etc.\n\nLocal gun manufacturers only make copies and are not very scientific in their manufacturing, hence they may not be aware of the methods used to compute the required twist rate for their weapons, especially because the twist rate is computed for a specific ammo to be used in a specific weapon, like in military weapons.\n\nThere have been many experts who derived their own formulas to compute barrel twist rate, one very commonly used was derived by Greenhill, known as Greenhill equation to copute barrel twist rate is as under.\n\nT'' = 150 / L'' \n\nwhere the twist and the bullet length are in calibers. Removing bullet diameter from twist and length gives the equation often found: \n\nT = 150 * D^2 / L \n\nThe Greenhill equation includes no term for muzzle velocity, and several sources suggest replacing the 150 with 180 for muzzle velocities over 2800 fps. Increasing muzzle velocity increases bullet spin, and spin provides the stability. An article in the 11/2001 Single Shot Exchange cites an article by Les Bowman in the 1962 Gun Digest offering an equation which includes muzzle velocity (in fps): \n\nT = 3.5 * V^0.5 * D^2 / L \n\nAt 2800 fps, this equation is equivalent to using 185 in the Greenhill equation, and at 1840 fps, this equation is the same as Greenhill''s.', ''),
