(34774, ' [quote]btw whats a roll crimp an how is it differnt from a star one. . .an while we are at it? whats a crimp anyway?[/quote]\n\ncrimping is: closing the business end of a shotgun cartridge.\nstar crimp: if u look at u''r regular No. 4, No. 8 shaheen cartridges, the mouth of the cartridge is crimped in a way that resembles a star\nRoll Crimp: also called disc crimped, if u look at shaheen''s SG cartridges, a flat circular disc is placed at the mouth of the cartridge to close it. its called roll crimped.\n\n\nmy humble opinion:\n\nRoll crimp is more efficient packing wise, it leaves more space for the shot load, powder and wadding however roll crimp suffers from pattern efficiency. star crimp leaves less space for the shotload, powder and wad (look at typical loading data, says to leave atleast 0.25 inch for the star crimp whereas roll crimp only needs 0.125 inch) however star crimp is more pattern friendly.\n\nReason: all petals of the star in a star crimp open with the same force at the same time where as in a roll crimp the circular disc doesnt leave the shell evenly, causing the pressure to leak out unevenly, thats why where pattern efficiency is required star crimp is the global standard and where high load is desired, roll crimped is prefered around the world.\n\nRegards.', ''),
