(35115, ' [quote=Moeen]Guys why would you want hollow point???  All bullets kill, hollow points were mainly developed in the states to stop over penetration - meaning stop at the terminal target only.  What was and has happened many times is when a cop has shot a criminal the bullet over  penetrates and makes its way through the body and hits someone else.  This ofcourse has meant lawsuits, this was one of the biggest contributing factor where the ammunition manufacturers who are catering to mainly law enforcement agencies developed these types of ammunitions.  The second factor is the sporting aspect such as bowling pin matches.  I have shot at many matches in my day and a standard jacketed round nose ammo would hit the bowling pin and go right through without making the bowling pin fall from the stand.  Hence when I used hollowpoints the pin would litterally fly off the table... having said that don''t anyone assume that the same will happen with humans.  This is Pakistan, and most of us are NOT employed by any LE agency.[/quote]\n\nOver panetration espacly wiht powerful calibres is an issue everywhere in the world. Lawsuit or no law suit. i wont want a round fired by me to hit an innocent bystander... Besides a mushrooming HP rips through muscle an sinew an bone an if it does exit it takes a whole heap of Bg with it...unlike the standard ball ammo that drills a hole. \n\nThats not to say that FMJs are less deadly..  But from a personal responsibility point of view i would prefer hp/jhps', ''),
(35116, ' [quote=106]Oho I''m sorry if I couldnt convey my message properly....I understood what you were saying the first time around.\n  I just meant to say that when Abbas Bhai mentioned soft cases Gown House popped into mind because I''m from Pindi too but after reading your post I thought I would ask you how much of a price difference they are charging and what is the other gun related stuff that you like there or think one can only get from there because yes they do have fascinating stuff which I''ve always been fascinated by since I was young but I just want to increase my knowledge on the gun related stuff they have and what is well priced and what one should avoid buying from there as it will be available elsewhere.\n  For example I saw a gun cleaning kit or like soft cases but then I did not have a shotgun but InshAllah soon when i do I was thinking of going there and I just want to learn from your experience \n  Plus could you please explain what a HIVIZ fibre optic bead is?\n Sorry for not explaining my question in a better way before.\n Regards.[/quote]\n\nbrother, compared to Lahore or Karachi, Gown House in my opinion charges three to four times as much for a similar item. regular running items such as hoppes and cheap cleaning rods are like twice as expensive at Gown House.\n\nas far as hunting apparel is concerned, brother dont even ask, he sells hunting vest/jackets but demands customer''s skin along with the price.\n\nabout HIVIZ:\n\nwell, hiviz is a manufacturer of fiber optic beads, these replace ur standard factory installed regular brass beads for better visibility. available in many shapes and sizes for various hunting/shooting situations.\n\nRegards.', ''),
(35117, ' [quote=SanSyed]dear pak gunners.\ni m willing to buy .17 caliber in Sako Varmint ,actually ths iz my frds gun and he iz selling ths,but i dont hv any information  regd it is a prohibted or non prohibted boar?some arms dealers said that ths is NPB and some said PB.so plz help me out!\nregds[/quote]\n\n.17 is roughly 4.5mm equilvalent to an air gun pallet, though a little heavier and longer than the pallet. An airgun pallet is propelled by the release of compressed air, where as .17 HMR / Mach2 is propelled by the expanding gases resulting from the burning gun powedr like in a firearm.\n\nThese bullets usually weigh 17 or 20 grains and reach up to 2550 fps. they are flat shooters upto 150 meters, and bullet drop is usually 3~4 inches for 17 grain and 8~9 inches for 20 grain.  \n\nThis is a varminter round meant for squirrels etc. or for punching paper targets.', ''),
