(35377, ' @12G, SS and HJ, please help with this problem:\n\nHave to clean up a CZ-27 1949-made. Hasn''t been used in more than a decade. the slide has much of the original bluing but the frame(body?) has lost some of the finish. If you pull back the slide, the outer surface of barrel has lost its luster and slightly rusted all over. Inside of barrel is also uniformly rusted. According to a website, to strip it, its slide should lock somewhere in the middle of the pull, on an empty mag. Then the little pin near the top of the trigger guard is pushed through to the other side to start dis-assembly. The pin on our piece doesn''t budge as if its welded...\n\nPlease guide about how it should be cleaned? Is stripping necessary for a thorough cleaning after so long a period? Can the cleaning mixes suggested by 12gauge be used in this case? If so, should i keep it dipped in cleaner/solvent etc? AND what is the level of safe usability of a firearm after such a long period of neglect and no maintenance? can''t post pics right now because my cell with cam is dead... :(\n\n[img]http://i958.photobucket.com/albums/ae62/pea_shooter/CZ27.jpg[/img]\n\nI posted the same ram kahani in the thread Gun Rust but haven''t got a response... :|', ''),
(35379, ' I would like to carry a GLOCK', ''),
(35380, ' It is a Made in Croatia, handgun for Springfield Armoury USA. Like glock it is a short recoil, striker fired, plymer frame pistol with high cap magazines.\n\nXD-9 began its life as the HS-2000, which itself was an improved version of I.M. Metalworks (Karlovac, Croatia) HS-95 of 1995. But it actually first appeared as the PHP in 1991, that particular pistol had a few quality control problems. Vukovic''s design team continually refined the PHP and HS-95, correcting its design and metallurgical weaknesses, the final version being designated as the HS-2000. Shortly thereafter, Springfield Armory acquired importation rights and re-designated the weapon as the XD-9.\n\nVisually the pistol looks to be a compact, the approximate equivalent of the Glock 19 or 23. It has fixed high-visibility sights of the tried-and-true 3-dot horizontal pattern to aid in low-light shooting, a nice 4.0 lbs trigger,  a grip safety and no sharp edges of any real significance.', ''),
