(371756, ' :sad:[QUOTE=Arslan_tareen;210310]I would also like to add that , if some one tells any of us Hunters that he can facilitate "Cheer Pheasant" hunt in "you know where" we should give him a slap on his neck and kick on his back .\r\nPlease note that 15-10 years ago cheer Pheasant went extinct in the wild , and a great effort was launched to restore this mystical bird , Dhudyial peasantry was created for such reason but alas all the efforts of there rehabilitation have officially failed and only about 3.4%  of bird introduced back in wild are said to be breeding , one reason behind it was that the birds were released in areas very near to human population specifically one place which had a fully carpeted road going through its habitat , around 75 % of the birds released in the wild were poached by hunters in first 2 years .[/QUOTE]\r\nYou are very right brother. Apart from the reason you pointed out there are numerous others, contributing to their scarce numbers in wild, such as, untrained staff handling them at the mentioned pheasantry, improper rearing of these birds under controlled conditions, improper planning at the time of their release,etc.I am sure their handlers never thought of the fact that, these were being reared to be released in the [B]WILD[/B] where conditions are tough to survive.There is a lot of difference between rearing for domestication,sport,and wild.\r\nThe rehabilitation project (in fact there were 2 of which i know.one in the capital territory on the Margalla hills forest reserve and another in Malakandi reserve , Kagan valley) you mentioned was unsuccessful because of improper planning of the concerned people who only want to gobble funds allocated for such projects and give a " Saab Acchha Hai" ki report to their superiors.As you all might know that as a nation we have gone into a habbit of applying cosmetics to wounds.Its a pitty.\r\nRegards.', ''),
