(35925, ' [quote=Conceal Carry][quote=Enigmatic Desires]The cougar has a rotating barrel that helps in eliminating muzzle flip repeat target acquisition.\n[/quote]\n\n\nWrong. A rotating barrel mechanim is to lock the slide momentarily so that it does not cycle untill the pressure of expanding gases has fallen to a level at which the slide can safely cycle without breaking off the frame.[/quote]\n\nOh.. An article in combat handguns mag stated so... something about muzzle flip being noticeably lighter in the rotating barrel pistol then in the non-rotating ones.. This is really the main reason why i preferred the cougher over any other weapon.. \n\nI have not had a chance to fire it.. hence the reason for this thread', ''),
(35926, ' Seems like i have opened a Pandora''s Box which is turning out to be extremely good discussion.\n@Glocky\nI dont consider the original Russian Luger to be bad ammo as such thing has never happened to my 24/7 or any of my friend''s using that ammo. This is not a normal case that might be related to FTF or FTE, its a case where shell was ejected while the bullet was stuck half way of the barrel and complete gun powder was burned inside the Pistol. Bad Ammo, i dont think so here. Its bad Manufacturing by Taurus. I dont that with so much power provided by the gun powder, a bullet should ever be lodged like that halfway through the barrell.', ''),
(35928, ' [quote=Adeel Ahmad]Seems like i have opened a Pandora''s Box which is turning out to be extremely good discussion.\n@Glocky\nI dont consider the original Russian Luger to be bad ammo as such thing has never happened to my 24/7 or any of my friend''s using that ammo. This is not a normal case that might be related to FTF or FTE, its a case where shell was ejected while the bullet was stuck half way of the barrel and complete gun powder was burned inside the Pistol. Bad Ammo, i dont think so here. Its bad Manufacturing by Taurus. I dont that with so much power provided by the gun powder, a bullet should ever be lodged like that halfway through the barrell.[/quote]\n\nTher could be two possible reasons that i can think of,\n1- Insufficient charge: There is a possibility that the round had less than required charge, which pushed the projectile out of the casing and in to the barrel, but did not provide enough force to push it all the way through the barrel.\n\n2- Charge dampened by moisture: This is another possibility, and the chances are that if it was due to ammo, this could really be it. The moisture somehow got into the casing and destroyed most of the powder, which did not burn and thus the blast of gas produced was not enough to push the bullet all the way through the barrel.\n\n3- The dia of the bullet was somewhat larger than the one which could easily pass through the barrel.\n\nWhen you get out the lodged bullet, inspect it for dia and compare it with others of the same lot.\nDo not fire remaining bullets of the same lot in this or any other gun.\nDO NOT TRY TO PULL THE LODGED BARELL. PUSH IT ALL THE WAY THROUGH MUZZLE END. or you will destroy the barrel.\nOnce the bullet is out, check the barrel for a "BULGE"on inside and outside, if any present, change the barel.\n\nPost results for everyones benefit.', ''),
