(36621, ' I''m a new member here and some of this info may be a repeat of what you already know.\nI will assume that some of you are unfamiliar with some things in Canada and make this post on that basis.\n\nWe have several levels of government that regulate firearms ownership, usage and hunting.\n\nThe country is divided into provinces[states]. \n\nThe federal [national] government sets regs in our criminal code.\n\nThe provinces fine tune these regs and add hunting rules to them. \n\nThen smaller governments,[city, county] add further restrictions as to where a firearm may be discharged etc.\n\n\nTo own, borrow, buy or possess a firearm in Canada requires a federal permit. To obtaim that permit an individual must take a course. The course is approx. 10 hours for long guns and an additional 6 hours for handguns. It includes instruction re: safety, function, storage and laws pertaining to different types of firearms. There is a written test as well as a practical test.\n\nI am a federal firearms instructor, and have put approx 400 students through the course.\n\nThere are background checks for criminal records etc.\n\nOnce the permit is issued. The individual can buy as many firearms as they wish with some restrictions.  Assault type rifles and handguns require a different level of instruction and a different permit.\n\nAll firearms must be registered by the owner in a national registry.\n\nThe provincial and city governments will also have some restrictions as to how where and when firearms may be used within their boundaries.\n\nIf a person wants to hunt, they must take a provincial hunter education course. This course requires about 25 hours of instruction and a written and practical test. The hunt course covers ethics, safety, firearms functions, wildlife identification, archery hunting, survival etc.\n\nI''ve been a provincial hunting instructor since 1975 and have lost track of how many students I have put through the course.\n\nWe are fortunate in Alberta in that we have  terrain and an abundance of wildlife and birds to hunt. We do not have a large population of hunters, but we do have access to a large and base to hunt on. This made up of both public and private land.\nthe terrain ranges from large rugged and isolated mountain ranges to open gras plains and everything between. \n\nAlberta is about 661,848 km2  in area and has a population of 3.6 million. Most of those are in the cities of course, so we can go fro days hunting and not see another person.\n\nHere''s a link to some information about Alberta.\n\n[url]http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alberta[/url]\n\nIf you have any questions, fire away:D i''ll try to answer them. I''ve posted soem pics in the hunting forum. I''ll get some more up when I get a chance.', ''),
(36622, ' i have a glock 17 and taurus pt 99 and found that there is not much difference in recoil , glock have earned thier fame due to thier reliability and accessories availbilty and although here they are expensive but in usa they are almost half the price of SIG and HKs', ''),
