(36632, ' I know of no one who eats wolves or coyotes, though I love to cook and have been sorely tempted to cook some coyote  Tacos for my inlaws.:D:D:D\n\nA Chinese restaurant was reported a couple years ago with some skinned and dressed coyotes in the walk in cooler. I asked my Chinese friends about it. They said in china dogs are common table fare and in Canada the coyote, because it is wild would be something special:rolleyes:\n\nI have eaten Mountain lion and it was excellent. \n\nI also have hunted and eaten a couple different types of deer, elk, moose, mountain goat, bighorn sheep, caribou, bison. and pronghorn antelope.\n\nI also hunted South Africa a few years ago and ate many things I enjoyed but didn''t have the courage to ask what it was at the time.:D\n\nWe also hunt and eat rabbits and hare. We have healthy populations of birds, so they sre also included in the menu in the fall. \n\nWe hunt bears spring and fall. Most everything else is fall hunting from Sept through December. By January the winter temperature is -20 to -40C  with snow on the ground till April so we hunt coyotes and wolves. It can be a challenge dealing with the cold..\n\nI like to take a week or so in Jan or Feb and hunt predators in the southern U.S> Arizona or New Mexico have daytime temperatures of 20C but it is plus not minus.:D', ''),
