(36645, ' The Penal Code is quite comprehensive regarding the rights of SD/HD.\n\nI think they are quite self explanatory.. :)\n\nAlso, learn by heart..\n\nLesson # 1.\n\n\n[b]Of the right of Private Defence[/b]\n\n96. Things done in private defence: Nothing is an offence which is done in the exercise\nof the right of private defence.\n\n97. Right of private defence of the body and of property: Every person has a right,\nsubject to the restrictions contained in Section 99, to defend;\n\n[b]First[/b]: His own body, [i]and the body of any other person[/i], against any offence affecting the\nhuman body;\n[b]Secondly[/b]: The property, whether movable or immovable,[i] of himself or of any other\nperson[/i], against any act which is an offence falling under the definition of [b]theft, robbery,\nmischief or criminal trespass, or which is an attempt to commit theft, robbery, mischief or\ncriminal trespass.[/b]\n\nEXAMPLE:\n(b) A enters by night a house which he is legally entitled to enter. Z in good faith, taking A\nfor a house-breaker, attacks A. Here Z by attacking A under this misconception, commits\nno offence. But A has the same right of private defence against Z, which he would have if\nZ were not acting under that misconception.', ''),
(36646, ' [b]99. Act against which there is no right of private defence: [/b]\n1. There is no right of private defence against an act which does not reasonably cause the apprehension of death\nor of grievous hurt, if done, or attempted to be done by a public servant acting in good\nfaith under colour, of his office, though that act may not be strictly justifiable by law.\n2. There is no right of private defence against an act which dose not reasonably\ncause the apprehension of death or of grievous hurt, if done, or attempted to be done, by\nthe direction of a [i]public servant acting in good faith under colour of his office[/i]([b] Police, tax collectors, postman etc[/b];) ) though that\ndirection may not be strictly justifiable by law. [b](Dont shoot them please!)[/b]\n[b]3. There is no right of private defence in cases in which there is time to have recourse to the\nprotection of the public authorities.\n[/b]\n[b]Extent to which the right may be exercised : [/b]The right of private defence in [b]no\ncase extends to the inflicting of more harm than it is necessary to inflict for the purpose of\ndefence.[/b]\nExplanation 1 :A person is not deprived of the right of private defence against an act done,\nor attempted to be done, by a public servant, as such, unless he knows, or has reason\nto believe, that the person doing the act is such public servant.', ''),
(36647, ' [b]100. When the right of private defence of the body extends to causing death[/b]: The\nright of private defence of the body extends, under the restrictions mentioned in the last\npreceding section, to the voluntary causing of death or of any other harm to the assailant,\nif the offence which occasions the exercise of the right be of any of the descriptions\nhereinafter enumerated, namely:--\n[b]First: Such an assault as may reasonably cause the apprehension that death will\notherwise be the consequence of such assault;[/b]\nSecondly : Such an assault as may reasonably cause the apprehension that [i]grievous hurt\nwill otherwise be the consequence of such assault;[/i]\n[i]Thirdly: An assault with the intention of committing rape;\nFourthly: An assault with the intention of gratifying unnatural lust.\nFifthly: An assault with the intention of kidnapping or abduction.\nSixthly: An assault with the intention of wrongfully confining a person[/i], under\ncircumstances which may reasonably cause him to apprehend that he will be unable to\nhave recourse to the public authorities for his release.', ''),
(36648, ' [b]101. When such right extends to causing any harm other than death:[/b] If the offence\nbe not of any of the descriptions enumerated in the last preceding section, the right of\nprivate defence of the body dose not extend to the voluntary causing of death to the\nassailant, but dose extend, under the restrictions mentioned in Section 99 to the voluntary\ncausing to the assailant of any harm other than death.\n\n\n[b]102. Commencement and continuance of the right of private defence of the body:[/b]\nThe right of private defence of the body [b]commences as soon as[/b] a reasonable\napprehension .of danger to the body arises from an attempt [b]or threat[/b] to commit the\noffence t[i]hough the offence may not have been committed[/i]; [b]and it continues as long as\nSuch apprehension of danger to the body continues.[/b]', ''),
(36649, ' This was [i][b]Self Defense[/b][/i]\n\nFor Home/ Property defense.. \n\n[b]103. When the right of private defence of [u]property[/u] extends to [u]causing death[/u][/b]: \n\nThe right of private defence of property extends, under the restrictions mentioned in Section\n99, to the voluntary Causing of death or of any other harm to the wrong-doer, if the\noffence, the committing of which, or the attempting to commit which, occasions the\nexercise of the right, be an offence of any of the descriptions hereinafter enumerated,\nnamely:-\nFirst: [b]Robbery[/b];\nSecondly : House-breaking[b] by night[/b];\nThirdly : Mischief by fire committed on any building, tent or vessel, which building, tent or\nvessel is used as a human dwelling or as a place for the custody of property;\nFourthly : [b]Theft, mischief or house-trespass[/b], under such circumstances as may\n[i]reasonably cause apprehension that death or grievous hurt will be the consequence, if\nsuch right of private defence is not exercised.[/i]\n\n104. When such right extends to causing any harm other than death : If the offence,\nthe committing of which, or the attempting to commit which, occasions the exercise of the\nright of private defence, be theft, mischief or criminal trespass, not of any of the\ndescriptions enumerated in the last preceding section that right dose not extend, to the\nvoluntary causing of death, but dose extend, subject to the restrictions mentioned\nin Section 99, to the voluntary causing to the wrong-doer of any harm other than death.', ''),
(36650, ' These are excerpts taken from the Pakistan Penal Code. I think a soft copy of the entire text is available in pdf format. Kindly keep that in your PCs and cell phones/PDAs etc, and dont let anybody tell you any different, because this law is quite clear and absolute.\n\nShooting someone in SD having daunting legal proceedings.. I think you are referring to US laws.. where the victim usually sues and wins..and there is a lengthy procedure..\n\nOr a friend of a friend of a friend told me so...\n\nIn Pakistan its very clear and simple. But you would have to prove in Court that the person you have just blown apart was fulfilling the above circumstances..\n\nNobody likes scumbags prowling around anyones home, its headache for the judge, pain in the *** for the police, and less paperwork for everyone involved..', ''),
