(36968, ' We''ve got one! SxS 12 Guage. Its light as walking stick...Actually, it is with my father.  GECO is the abbreviation of [b]Gustav Genschow & Co., [/b] subsidiary of the Company, founded 1912, former manufacturer of pistol and revolver cartridges.Since April 2002, the Swiss ammunition manufacturer RUAG Munition and Dynamit Nobel AmmoTec in Germany have merged their ammunition businesses and now form the RUAG Ammotec company – the new key player in ammunition technology and from January 2005 Gustav Genschow "Nobel" is renamed RUAG Ammotec Austria. Today RUAG Ammotec Austria GmbH is the distributor for civil ammunition of the RUAG group in Austria and many countries in Eastern Europe and Latin America, as well as representative of many other important brands in Austria, as REMINGTON, RIO, GLOCK, ANSCHÜTZ, TITAN, NORINCO, DIANA, KAHLES, MEOPTA, OPTOLYTH, EAW-Apel, GFT-WEGU, LYMAN-PACHMAYR, SICKINGER, BARNETT, etc. For export they offer also WALTHER, SIG, H&K, CZ, and more to some countries.\nThere earlier models were named Gustav as I have seen some...A friend has one with 32" barrels and we call it canon :) Rifles produced by Geco were named Gecado. Geco were also known for production of First Ever Botl Action 12 Guage Shotgun :) the gun used to be known as GEHA and its nickname was HHH (Hard Heart Hitter). \nGustav Genschow OR Geco were an early manufacturer of such guns…this company also made single-shot .22 S-L-LR rifles in the 1920’s.  Due to Jewish ownership, however, the Third Reich redistributed Genschow’s assets to Nazi-friendly companies such as Gustloff-Werke. And later story is as above! i.e RUAG taking over...\nAnyways guns made by GECO are good! prices are moderate depending on the condition!!!! That''s all I know about it :)', ''),
(36969, ' [b]GECO History \n[/b]\n[url]http://www.genschow.com/English/Firma_e/firma_e.htm[/url]\n\nGeco is still in business today, as a subsidiary of Dynamit Nobel. [url]http://www.dnrws.com/products.html[/url] \n\nThey were not manufacturers, just distributors of contract built guns.\n\nGeco did not make or distribute shotguns after WW2. The company is best known as a manufacturer of ammunition, and that is what the brand name is used for today.\n\nSource: [url]http://www.shotgunworld.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=76321[/url]', ''),
