(37434, ' and bhatti sab what about chokes. did they offer removable chokes or did you specify what you needed? 12G says i''ll have to specify the kind of choke i need. i think that means they won''t offer removable ones...\n\nguys i hope i''m not trailing off the topic  \n[url=http://www.postimage.org/][img]http://www.postimage.org/templates/images/smiley/confused/5.gif[/img][/url]', ''),
(37435, ' I am no expert but Local Shotgun clones are fine for occasional use. DSA is even better. Stay away from Handguns as they tend to be unreliable mostly.', ''),
(37436, ' [quote]Turumti Wrote:\n\nWhy do you reccomend against an MP153 with extended chokes?\n\nAlso what do you think of Carlson extended chokes? Do you think they perform as well the maufacturers claim they do? Are they worth buying?[/quote]\n\nI recommend against MP153 only when the said shotgun is not available with flush mounted chokes. in my experience extended chokes supplied with Baikal MP153 are steel rated only, hence more open chokes, therefore more wider patterns with lead shots. I also have three extended chokes and have always found their patterns to be less than ideal with lead, with steel shot however they are fine. but since in Pakistan most shooting is done with lead shots, its pointless to have "steel rated only" choke tubes.\n\ni''ve heard about carlsons but cant say much about them, If u''r thinking of buying aftermarket chokes to improve patterns then go for Trulock (i''ve ordered four for my cousin and used them) or colonial arms. as far as these two manufacturers are concerned, their chokes definately improve patterns and are true to their advertisement/claim.\n\nRegards', ''),
