(38195, ' Since rear sights are dovetail they just need to be slide out from one side to another. You can use a special pushing tool made by various companies including Glock or a Flat head screw driver with a wooden mallet. The front sights are tricky because not all of the front sights have screws. some of them are crimped i.e. once the sight passes thru to hole the base opens up. You also need to apply some adhesive (loctite) to make sure it remains in place. Hope that helps. \n\nI just need to decide which night sight is the best overall.', ''),
(38196, ' Glocky is right that its the Front Sight which is always difficult to install and he didn''t say that its difficult to unistall. You can screw it up pretty bad while installation and you have to be expert for that. I have used Tru Glow sights but never installed them myself just it on a Friend''s Hand Gun. Target acquisition is much better with that but according to the reviews by other people i think you should go for Trijicon.', ''),
