(38376, ' This topic has already been discussed! "THOROUGHLY" :) Information & Knowledge levels of members were challenged as well :)) The mystery of NPB & PB in terms of rifles is based on the licences issued by MOI and that issued by provincial government! Ministry Of Interior considers any calibre (OF RIFLES) above .22 (Bolt Action) as a PB!!! And for the issuance of licence there is a set proceadure where earlier Prime minister''s senction was required but later it was transfered to Interior Minister! On the other hand provincial governments i.e. Sind, Punjab & N.W.F.P. do not consider rifles as a PB but licence I beleive restricts you to carry the weapon from one province to the other! Charm of the licence issued by MOI is the permission to carry the weapon all over Pakistan. It is my knowledge so far ;) Now, this is the reason....whenever members from Capital or rawalpindi give their comments they confirm such rifles as a PB & those from Sind always take it as a NPB. I always say we have different experiences and this forum is meant to provide us a platform to share it. In earlier discussion couple of members got confused and instead of realizing the nature/base of information, started challenging the source of information and knowledge levels of each other :) That''s little absurd I believe! Sharing the experience means asking more details politely and there is nothing wrong in giving details :|', ''),
(38378, ' Accoding to MOI Auth, all type of Rifles are P Bore execpt .22 rifle. No dealer is auth to sell a P bore rifle. Two options: 1- From licence to licence thr DCO/DC office (2) Gift by Maliks thr PA', ''),
(38380, ' In summary, the extract of the above discussion can be:\nFOR RIFLES\n1. [u]MOI licenses allow ONLY .22 bolt-actions as NPB[/u] & the rest calibers & actions as PB.\n2. [u]Sindh Govt. allows all calibers in bolt-action as NPB[/u] and semi-auto & auto actions as PB.\n3. [u]Pujab Govt. allows ONLY .22 caliber in bolt-action & semi-auto as NPB[/u] and all other calibers as PB regardless of their action.\n\nEXCEPT one unique case as confirmed by Denovo87 from his personal experience.', ''),
