(38657, ' Is ankle holster a strong preference or are you open to other suggestions?\n\nIMHO it is wayyy over rated and far from ideal.. like a last resort.. and it is in a dust loving area (especially in our country) and you would certainly not want a semi auto in a position there.. if so go for revolver.. air lite sort of thing.)\n\nGlock 19 is one of the LEAST over priced guns available here.. i would suggest grrab em while you can..\n\nStoeger Cougar.. dont own one yet.. but am also looking to get one as a beater.. but have heard good things.. \nHowever I dont think it would fit easily in the ankle.. ( you may want to see sub compacts for that).. It IS bulky..\n\nIncidentally.. what is your rough body size, height, build, hand size etc? That would help us in helping you out..\n\nGlock 26 I have heard nothing but good things about it.. \n\nGlock 19 is a great all rounder and is balanced and reliable.. but you either love it or hate it.. \n\nThere is a Taurus I saw ... Titanium one.. Millenium something.. It felt nice to hold and light.. but I would let the Taurus experts handle this one.. dont go for this on my advice as I cannot give you a view on its performance.. Though I''m sure our knowledge banks would be sure to help you out..\n\nAlso... Norinco TT type things are quite slim.. and the criminals first choice of concealed carry.. and they seem to be doing pretty well with it.. so why not!\n\nLastly.. The HOLSTER choice is more important than the handgun.. a good holster can conceal even full sized weapons..\n\nTry to find a single stack 9mm compact if you can.. I think thats the best option for total concealed carry.. \n\nIf you can afford it.. get a glock.. you cant go wrong with it.. but if its not your first handgun, it WILL take time to get used to its weird steep grip angle.. See the market place section on this website for approx price of both the Glocks..\n\nFor bullets.. I have always used POF for practice.. and they''ve always worked.. (except once I tried some sten gun ones made in 1950s.. some of them were duds.. but most still worked!). However my friends at Pakguns got me to try Chinese and They worked equally well and a lot cleaner I must admit..\n\nI would say stay away from local unbranded ones and you''ll do just fine.. HOWEVER make sure your gun likes ammo.. Even the best guns dislike particular brands so fire a good number of different ammo to see which suits your jewel the best..\n\nIn the end I would say Happy Shopping and Happy Shooting.. (preferably NOT TOGETHER!!!) j/k :D', ''),
(38658, ' I''ve got six words for you my friend\n\nH & K USP\n\nIts DESIGNED to be carried locked and cocked..\n\nHas 4 safeties internal and external..\n\nNeed I say more?\n\nactually yes.. \n\nA P7M13 if you can find one.. squeeze cocker.. such a darling of a gun..\n\nAhh... I''m so in love with them.. (but lets not both of them find out about the other being in my life.. I dont want them feeling jealous while pointing at the "wrong" things.)', ''),
(38659, ' Yes but please do be careful.. snap caps and live rounds have this thing going on.. the bad habit of getting mixed up till you dont know what is what.. \n\nAlways take full precautions.. I liked it when someone said he leaves all his live ammo in a SEPARATE room when he practices dry firing at home.. I think we should all adopt this practice.. \n\nAt the range I suppose it is okay since your always pointing downrange anyway so doesnt really matter..\n\nOnce again I would stress.. BE ATTENTIVE.. it can save a lot of embarrassment at the least and at worse... ......:o', ''),
(38660, ' [color=red]Thank you. My answers are in red. Appreciate you help.[/color]\n\nIs ankle holster a strong preference or are you open to other suggestions?  [color=red]No. Desirable not mandatory[/color]\n\nIMHO it is wayyy over rated and far from ideal.. like a last resort.. and it is in a dust loving area (especially in our country) and you would certainly not want a semi auto in a position there.. if so go for revolver.. air lite sort of thing.)\n\nGlock 19 is one of the LEAST over priced guns available here.. i would suggest grrab em while you can..[color=red]It appears to be a really good piece of equipment. It is just that the PKR versus the USD price does not stack up, export restrictions notwithstanding[/color]\n\nStoeger Cougar.. dont own one yet.. but am also looking to get one as a beater.. but have heard good things.. \nHowever I dont think it would fit easily in the ankle.. ( you may want to see sub compacts for that).. It IS bulky..[color=red]I don''t suppose there is a compact version of the Cougar?[/color]\n\nIncidentally.. what is your rough body size, height, build, hand size etc? That would help us in helping you out..[color=red]6''2"; 90 kilos; hands not disproportionately large or small[/color]\n\nGlock 26 I have heard nothing but good things about it.. \n\nGlock 19 is a great all rounder and is balanced and reliable.. but you either love it or hate it.. \n\nThere is a Taurus I saw ... Titanium one.. Millenium something.. It felt nice to hold and light.. but I would let the Taurus experts handle this one.. dont go for this on my advice as I cannot give you a view on its performance.. Though I''m sure our knowledge banks would be sure to help you out..[color=red]Some Taurus models appear to have reliability issues which has put me off them[/color]\n\nAlso... Norinco TT type things are quite slim.. and the criminals first choice of concealed carry.. and they seem to be doing pretty well with it.. so why not![color=red]Fair enough. Are they reliable and durable (given the reasonable price)?[/color]\n\nLastly.. The HOLSTER choice is more important than the handgun.. a good holster can conceal even full sized weapons..[color=red]What sort of a holster would you recommend? Given that, in all probability, one would have to order it over the internet without being able to physically check it out it would be a bit of a lucky dip, I suppose.[/color]\n\nTry to find a single stack 9mm compact if you can.. I think thats the best option for total concealed carry.. [color=red]Any suggestions given local availability? What is the number of rounds a single stack compact would normally hold?[/color]\n\nIf you can afford it.. get a glock.. you cant go wrong with it.. but if its not your first handgun, it WILL take time to get used to its weird steep grip angle.. See the market place section on this website for approx price of both the Glocks..[color=red]Unlikely....until the EU ban comes off or some ''smart'' trader in Dubai figures out a way to bring them in at a reasonable mark-up [/color]\n\nFor bullets.. I have always used POF for practice.. and they''ve always worked.. (except once I tried some sten gun ones made in 1950s.. some of them were duds.. but most still worked!). However my friends at Pakguns got me to try Chinese and They worked equally well and a lot cleaner I must admit..\n\nI would say stay away from local unbranded ones and you''ll do just fine.. HOWEVER make sure your gun likes ammo.. Even the best guns dislike particular brands so fire a good number of different ammo to see which suits your jewel the best..\n\nIn the end I would say Happy Shopping and Happy Shooting.. (preferably NOT TOGETHER!!!) j/k [color=red]Thanks. And, I will try to fight the temptation :)[/color]', ''),
