(38715, ' [b]AoA Everybody![/b]\n\nJust thought I should share something regarding the merits and demerits of the two most encountered types of shotgun stocks. Plus it’s Sunday and I’m sorta keeping myself busy or rather unavailable. ( I’m sure any married man would understand)\n\n[b]1. English Stock AKA Straight Grip or English Grip:[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.gunsinternational.com/images/listings/100036245-5-L.jpg[/img]\n\nEnglish stock was originally designed to allow quick selection of the rear trigger on a double trigger gun. The design also allowed the gun to be just a tab bit lighter, sleeker and easier to swing. Since the angle of the wrist is less awkward, the gun also becomes easier in field carry.\n\nHowever the benefits of this stock design comes at a price, the operator essentially loses right hand control over the shotgun. Meaning, the operator lets go of some of the right hand control and relies more on the left hand, the hand that grips the forend (I’m assuming the shooter is right handed). With this sort of setup, the gun becomes difficult to maneuver. During mount there is more reliance on the left hand, however after a successful mount, since there is more reliance on the left hand, the swing is more controlled.\n\n[b]2. Prince of Wales Grip AKA Pistol Grip or Modified Pistol Grip:[/b]\n\n[img]http://www.gunsinternational.com/images/listings/100086136-3-L.jpg[/img]\n\nThe fact that most people call it pistol grip is wrong, it is actually modified pistol, originated by the prince of Wales who was weak in the right hand, he desired more control in the right hand therefore the modified pistol grip was born.\n\nWhile it is true that forehand is highly important in moving the barrel with the bird, the rear hand is equally important in maintaining gun mount and trigger control. Neither hand is more important. One hand should not be weakened just to improve the importance of the other.\n\nI’m sure by now you must have guessed that semi pistol or Prince of Wales grip takes some of the control from the left and puts it in the right hand. Therefore permits a more controlled mount, more authority over the trigger and increased maneuverability. Why it got popular? Hmmm.... quiet simple, the gain in the right hand control is greater than the loss in the control of the left hand. To put it short, gain in right hand control = huge, loss in left hand control = insignificant.\n\nThis type of grip proved to be quiet popular among hunters and sport shooters alike as it results in a more controlled mount, more control over the triggers, more maneuverability of the gun along with an excellent swing. A testimony to the success of a modified pistol grip is that English stocks are practically on the endangered species list in the sporting events around the globe. Competitive shooters of today, realizing the importance of control in both hands, almost always prefer modified pistol grips.\n\nHope it helps, (it sure did for me, otherwise my wife had like a million home chores lined up for me today and everyone of them was a major turn-off).\n\n[b]Regards[/b]', ''),
