(39387, ' [quote=Abbas]Nice, this mod can be made to almost any bed. I think a carpenter and wielder worth of two days work each and about Rs. 7000 worth of materials should do the trick.[/quote]\n\nAbass Bhai, it looks like a neat thing but dont want to sound like a party pooper (nor want to rain on this parade) but here are some of my concerns:\n\n1. a simple wooden gun cabinet costs 7K-10K as i''ve made two myself, one for me, one for my best friend''s elder brother. from wooden i''m not  talking about real wood, i''m talking engineered wood (chipboard, plywood, my preference sheesham chipboard/plywood). therefore I dont think one could make a steel bed with 10 gauge sheets with a materials budget of 10K\n\n2. initially before moving on to gun cabinets, i was strictly a gun chest (made that myself as well) kinda person, fully enclosed space and sealed with guns neatly packed together fully assembled. but any guy who uses gun chests knows the menace of humidity and its adverse effects on steel. guns rust pretty easily in a humid and dark environment. some organism even grow on wooden gun parts if kept for long in dark and humid environment. solutions require constant heat/light source in the chest and its a real pain in the neck. otherwise options are to put silicone gels in the gun chest but then again they require periodical changing.\n\n3. when even long guns are placed/stored flat against any surface, they have a tendency to bend after extended storage duration.\n\n4. bolting all metal parts together will not work either, upon closer inspection it looks that sheet metal has been bent (process: SHEET METAL BENDING) and corners welded together, this would require services of an industrial welder, ordinary "TUCH" WELDERS are not upto the task.\n\n5. if u look at the bed closely, it looks like the bed shifts to make enough room for the gun safe''s door to open.  moving such a bed would require desigining of ball bearing which will have to move on a ramp, otherwise the bed will simply slide off to the other side.\n\n6. safe''s door construction seems to be of a typical hinge type, double sheet, internal lock mechanism, very difficult to custom make as it requires alot of technical know how.\n\nConsidering all these, I would say: given the lack of technical expertise, lack of economies of scale (which reduces price of such an item as specialized machines/tools are created to do a difficult job with ease), lack of materials available. designing/making such a thing would easily cross 100-150K.\n\nRegards\n\np.s. incase u guys wondering what kinda gun cabinet i can make. well... i''m no professional however since i love woodwork and tend to be very careful with my calculations (ok i admit I usually solicit the services of a maths genius cousin of mine), the projects turn out not too bad (if i do say so myself).\n\nhere it is, this one I''ve recently made like 2 months ago (for my friend''s elder brother).\n\nstorage space: 8 guns\nMaterial: all 3/4inch sheesham plywood construction (all sides/walls made of 0.75inch sheet of sheesham plywood, back/bottom/top, resulting in a much solid contruction)\nentry: sliding glass (tempered glass) locked by simple sliding glass lock\nbottom storage: simple pull down type door, with round knobs, lock and key setup\npriority: to keep the overall profile down, I had to exclude skirting and crown.\nTotal Cost: 8K (all materials as i did everything myself, except glass fixing). for polishing/varnish/paint/sealing, add another 2K.\n\n[img]http://img199.imageshack.us/img199/6870/32877225.jpg[/img]\n\n[img]http://img35.imageshack.us/img35/981/74973036.jpg[/img]\n\n[img]http://img35.imageshack.us/img35/4422/61192676.jpg[/img]\n\nRegards', ''),
