(39417, ' Can someone please let me know about the gunsmiths in Pak? What do you guys do if you need a gun repaired?\n\nI know a man in our village (in Pakistan) who people take their guns to for repairs etc, but am not sure as to the level of his competence.\n\nI''m sure there would be some very talented gun smiths around, but are there those who are known to be really good, those that could be truly described as master gunsmiths.\n\nAlso I assume that most gunsmiths would only be experts in certain common firearms in Pak such as TT''s, AK''s  etc.\n\nI think it would be good for members if we could  have some names of the best gunsmiths in the major cities, please share your experiences.\n\nI suppose for those who can travel to Darra easily that would be the best option for any repair work. Would it be O.K to trust someone you didn''t know with an expensive gun? I mean you wouldn''t want  to have your original internals exchanged for fake ones now would you  ;)', ''),
(39418, ' [quote=Taurus]well the only thing i hate about taurus is they use low quality metals as for 4" barrel and .357 magnum the cost is around 65k in khi and whats the purpose brother Abu hafs for buying is it just for self defence ? [/quote]\n\nWell yes the primary purpose of any weapon I would buy would be self defense. I think revolvers by and large are more reliable than semi autos, also the .357 is from what Ive read the best caliber for self defense. Revolvers have advantages over semi autos and vice versa. \n\n[quote]remember it has a bang voice and too much recoil..plus i dont think revolvers are even practical for self defence as they are not accurate even on 10 metres any revolver i have seen is not practical  [/quote]\n\n\nI don''t have any practical experience with revolvers bro but from my research I would have to disagree with your assertion that revolvers are inaccurate at even 10 meters.Many people  carry small frame revolvers for self defense and they report them to be very accurate at close range.Some of the larger revolvers are accurate to  50+ meters and are used for hunting large game.\n\nIts all a matter of personal preference, each to their own, different strokes for different folks as they say.', ''),
(39419, ' For the less experienced shooter, the semi-auto is more prone to jams. This is fact, not opinion. A revolver is not subject to these jams and is, therefore, a more reliable weapon. There is little that can go wrong with a revolver in an emergency. If a round were to fail to fire for some reason, all you have to do is to pull the trigger again and a new round will rotate up into the firing position.\n\nPerhaps your friend was speaking from a gunsmith''s position when he was talking about the difficulties in getting the timing of the cylinder set correctly. But once it is done at the factory, it will stay in time barring any unusual event or long time wear.\n\nThe bottom line is that from the standpoint of simplicity and reliability of operation, the revolver is the better choice. The main advantage of the semi-auto over a revolver is in the number of rounds it carries. The fact is that rarely does an actual gun fight, where you are defending yourself, go much beyond 2 or 3 rounds anyway. By that time, the bad guy is either on the ground or long gone. In fact, when they see a gun, he and his friends will scatter like quail without you even having to fire one shot.', ''),
(39420, ' If you are interested in compact gun then go for MAKAROV or walther ppk. I own both and both are compact and reliable guns. PPK is so small that you can even carry it in side pocket although it is .32 cal but can be very effective at close range.', ''),
