(40420, ' Stainless Steel is not exactly "stainless". In order to make steel totally rustproof (stainless), the carbon content has to be removed and chromium has to be added. If you remove all the carbon, the steel will become brittle and will not be suitable for use in firearms, knives, etc. So, for the manufacture of these products, some percentage of carbon has to be in steel (which determines hardness and ability to stand up to pressure). It is this carbon which slowly causes the oxygen in the air to react, forming brownish-orange iron oxide aka rust. I also infer that due to extreme barrel heat, this reaction occurs at a quicker rate.\n\nSo, the "stainless steel" we commonly use is not, repeat not, truly stainless or rustproof.', ''),
